eans, but because more and more Shakespearians agree that it is worth arguing about. The essays in this collected volume explore the ways in which we might approach Q1’s Hamlet, from performance to book history, from Shakespeare’s relationships with his contemporaries to the shape of his whole career.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aEnglish drama (Tragedy)xHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Shakespeare.2bisacsh  aCultural Studies (General), Literary Studies.1 aBourus, Terri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBourus, Terri, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBruster, Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aContinisio, Tommaso, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrampton, Saul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolderness, Graham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Laurie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Charles Adams, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoughnane, Rory, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoughrey, Bryan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarino, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCarthy, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNance, John V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPlehn-Peavyhouse, Dayna Leigh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTaylor, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWagoner, Michael M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel